  "preview": "Before Python, before GPUs my first AI was built with a soldering iron. In the 1990s, a ZX Spectrum an 8-bit home computer showed up in our house. And that was it. Love! One that, honestly, has lasted",
  "text": "Before Python, before GPUs 𝗺𝘆 𝗳𝗶𝗿𝘀𝘁 𝗔𝗜 𝘄𝗮𝘀 𝗯𝘂𝗶𝗹𝘁 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵 𝗮 𝘀𝗼𝗹𝗱𝗲𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗶𝗿𝗼𝗻. 🔧\n\nIn the 1990s, a 𝗭𝗫 𝗦𝗽𝗲𝗰𝘁𝗿𝘂𝗺 — an 8-bit home computer — showed up in our house. ❤️ And that was it. Love! One that, honestly, has lasted to this day.\n\nBack then it wasn't just a computer, it was a construction kit. You had to solder the keyboard — every single key. For real. Assemble the boards, put everything into a case.\n\nThe case was awful, by the way. So, I built my own — wooden. Moved the keyboard out separately. Console plus keyboard, my own vision, at age 8.\n\nAfter that I started programming. Small things, experiments. I wrote a couple of programs. I don't even remember what the first one was about, but there was an𝘢𝘭𝘨𝘰𝘳𝘪𝘵𝘩𝘮, and I made it work. That was enough for me back then.\n\nAround 2000, things got really interesting. I started reading a paper magazine called Computerra. It explained early AI research papers in plain language — the same ideas that later landed Hopfield and Hinton the 2024 Nobel in Physics. 🏆\n\nWhat fascinated me was the simplicity and beauty of how it actually works.\nThose papers suggested a simple idea: 𝘥𝘰𝘯'𝘵 𝘣𝘳𝘶𝘵𝘦-𝘧𝘰𝘳𝘤𝘦 𝘦𝘷𝘦𝘳𝘺𝘵𝘩𝘪𝘯𝘨 — 𝘤𝘶𝘵 𝘰𝘧𝘧 𝘥𝘦𝘢𝘥 𝘦𝘯𝘥𝘴 𝘦𝘢𝘳𝘭𝘺.\n\nI applied this to formal mathematical logic. Instead of hours or days, I got the Pythagorean theorem down to 30 minutes on an 80286. Just by teaching it to notice earlier: this makes no sense, we've already been here, this leads to a loop. 🔄\n\nThat was my first AI-related program. It made me a member of the Junior Academy of Sciences of Ukraine, in 11th grade.\n\nAnd I kept poking at it. Later I came up with a self-hosted GenAI system for banking document generation — basically a ChatGPT for German banking, built before ChatGPT existed. Now there's 𝗧𝗿𝘂𝗲𝗕𝗗𝗗, a small tool where documentation is the source of truth, so code can be deleted along the way.\n\nAI still interests me — what's inside it, why it works, and where its real limits are, and how it will change the way we build software forever.",
